      <p align=3D"left" class=3D"ArialRed20"><strong>PERIMETER:</strong><br=
>
        <span class=3D"TimesBlack16">The difficulty associated with finding=
 perimeter is based upon what information you are given regarding the polyg=
on. For example, if you are given the length of a side of a regular polygon=
, all you need to do is multiply the length by the number of sides to find =
the perimeter. It is, however, unlikely that a question will be that simple=
 in a Geometry course.</span></p>
      <p align=3D"left" class=3D"TimesBlack16">A <span class=3D"TimesBlue16=
">crucial area on which to focus, when working with regular polygons, </spa=
n>is the isosceles triangle formed by the radii of the polygon and one of i=
ts sides. Let's take a look at =CE=94<em>DOC</em> from the regular pentagon=
 shown at the beginning of this page.</p>
