      <p align=3D"left" class=3D"ArialRed20"><strong>AREA:</strong><br>
        <span class=3D"TimesBlack16">We saw under the "perimeter" section h=
ow to go about finding missing information about a regular polygon by exami=
ning the isosceles triangle formed by the radii of the polygon and one of i=
ts sides. This triangle will also be the key to finding the area of a regul=
ar polygon. When working with "area", we will be focused on the </span><spa=
n class=3D"TimesBlue16">altitude</span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">, and t=
he </span><span class=3D"TimesBlue16">side </span><span class=3D"TimesBlack=
16">of that isosceles triangle.</span></p>
      <table width=3D"750" border=3D"1" align=3D"center" cellpadding=3D"7" =
cellspacing=3D"0" class=3D"blackborder">
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td align=3D"center"><span class=3D"ArialBlack16">Regarding the=
se isosceles triangles, such as =CE=94DOC, we know:<br>
</span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">=E2=80=A2 </span><span class=3D"TimesBl=
ue16">the number of triangles =3D the number of sides of the regular polygo=
n</span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16"><br>
=E2=80=A2
</span><span class=3D"TimesBlue16">the triangles are congruent to one anoth=
er</span><span class=3D"TimesBlack16"><br>
Thus, if we know the area of one triangle, we will know the area of the ent=
ire polygon.</span></td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
