      <p align=3D"center" class=3D"ArialRed20"><strong><br>       =20
        Is there a "formula" for the area of a regular polygon?</strong></p=
>
      <p align=3D"left" class=3D"TimesBlack16">Yes! We just saw that using =
the strategy of partitioning, the areas of  regular polygons can be found b=
y adding together the areas of all of the congruent triangles formed by the=
 central angles and each side of the polygon.  This will be the basis for a=
n area formula.</p>
      <p align=3D"left" class=3D"TimesBlack16">Remember:  the area of a tri=
angle is <em>A</em>=3D =C2=BD<em>bh. </em>When dealing with a polygon, the =
<span class=3D"TimesBlue16">"base" </span>will be a <span class=3D"TimesBlu=
e16">"side of the polygon"</span> and the <span class=3D"TimesDarkRed16">"h=
eight" </span>will be the <span class=3D"TimesDarkRed16">"=CE=94's altitude=
 (which is the polygon's <strong>apothem</strong>)</span>.<br>
        </p>
      <table width=3D"710" border=3D"1" align=3D"center" cellpadding=3D"7" =
cellspacing=3D"0" class=3D"blackborder">
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td width=3D"690" align=3D"center"><span class=3D"TimesBlack16"=
>The <span class=3D"TimesBlue16">apothem of a regular polygon</span> is a l=
ine segment from the center of the polygon perpendicular to any side of the=
 polygon.</span></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p align=3D"left" class=3D"TimesBlack16">With a series of  substituti=
ons, we can arrive at a formula.<span class=3D"TimesBlack20"><br>
        </span><span class=3D"TimesBlack14">Remember that the number of  co=
ngruent triangles =3D the number of sides of the polygon.</span></p>
      <p align=3D"center" class=3D"TimesBlack20"><img src=3D"https://mathbi=
tsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/apothemperimeterformula.png" alt=3D"apothe=
mperimeterformula" width=3D"650" height=3D"164"></p>
      <table width=3D"471" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0"=
>
