        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td width=3D"381" valign=3D"top"><span class=3D"TimesBlack16">L=
et's take another look at the <strong>area </strong>of regular pentagon <em=
>ABCDE.</em> This time, let's apply the new formula.</span>
              <p class=3D"TimesBlack16">Triangle <em>DOC</em> is  an isosce=
les triangle in which the triangle's altitude is the polygon's <span class=
=3D"TimesBlue16">apothem (from <em>O</em> to <em>P</em>). </span> </p>
              <p class=3D"TimesBlack16">As was done in the previous example=
, we find <em>DC</em> and <em>OP</em> using trigonometry.<br>
                side: <em>DC</em> =3D 9.405 <br>
                apothem: <em>OP</em> =3D 6.472<br>
              </p>
				<span class=3D"TimesBlack16">The <span class=3D"TimesBlue16">area =3D =
=C2=BD <em>ap</em></span><em> </em>=3D =C2=BD (6.472)(47.025)</span><br>
                <span class=3D"TimesDarkRed16">A =3D 152 sq. in.</span><br>
                <span class=3D"TimesBlack12">(rounded to <em>nearest intege=
r</em>)</span></td>
            <td width=3D"353" align=3D"center"><span class=3D"ArialBlack16"=
>Regular Pentagon<br>
              </span><span class=3D"ArialBlack12">radius =3D 8 inches </spa=
n><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Geometry/Polygons/PentagonBIG.jp=
g" width=3D"306" height=3D"314" alt=3D""></td>
